erred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cydifor ap Rhys was born about 1238, in Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales as the son of Rhys ap Rhydderch of Castell Hywel and Catherine Ddes. He had at least 1 son with Rhys verch Gwenellian."},"et":{"ABT    1238–":"umbes 1238–Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1238":"1238","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1245":"1245","1160":"1160","1270":"1270","ABT    1238":"umbes 1238","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","{Cdfr ap Dnwl}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","of Castell Hywel,Llandysul,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales"},"fi":{"ABT    1238–":"noin 1238–Kuollut","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1238":"1238","about 1270":"noin 1270","1245":"1245","1160":"1160","1270":"1270","ABT    1238":"noin 1238","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","{Cdfr ap Dnwl}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italia","of Castell Hywel,Llandysul,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales"},"fr":{"ABT    1238–":"environ 1238–Décédé","1238–Male":"1238–Décédé","1245–Female":"1245–Décédée","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","